stitutional practices and values. Drawing on historical trends, survey statistics, and personal interviews with people in both countries, Yu shows how country-specific organizational arrangements and industrial policies affect women's employment. In particular, the conditions faced by Japanese and Taiwanese women in the workplace have a profound effect on their labor force participation at critical points in their lives. Women's lifetime employment decisions in turn shape the divergent trajectories in gender equality. Few studies documenting the development of women's economic lives are based on non-Western societies and even fewer adopt a comparative perspective. This perceptive work demonstrates and underscores the importance of understanding gender inequality as a long-term, dynamic social process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aSex discrimination against womenxJapan. 0aSex discrimination against womenxTaiwan. 0aSex discrimination against womenzJapan. 0aSex discrimination against womenzTaiwan. 0aSex discrimination in employmentxJapan. 0aSex discrimination in employmentxTaiwan. 0aSex discrimination in employmentzJapan. 0aSex discrimination in employmentzTaiwan. 0aWomenxEmploymentxJapan. 0aWomenxEmploymentxTaiwanxJapanxTaiwan. 0aWomenxEmploymentzJapan. 0aWomenxEmploymentzTaiwan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804771047zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804771047423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804771047.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles